But it is scarcely possible to explain in the same way, as due to the blundering eagerness of Da· masippus, the comparison of Stoi- cism to a morbus, even to a kind of frenzy. Though Horace has not actually put the word into the mouth of Damasippus the expres- sion is still quite clearly incon- sistent with his character, and we must say that Horace has here, as perhaps in vss. 19 and 33, failed to make the speech quite con· sistent with the character of the speaker.—The illustration in vs. 30-‘as some man (hic) in a lethargy suddenly turns boxer and assaults his doctor'—is chosen in order to give an open· ing for the remark in vs. 31 and to lead up to the subject of madness.
